Shell Types

Broune Shell (Sh Shell)
C Shell (csh or tcsh)
Z Shell (zsh)
Bourne again Shell (BASH)

ls -a                             #List files and folders
cd my_dir1                        #change directory
pwd                               #Present Working Directory
mkdir new_directory               #Make Directory
cd new_directory; mkdir www; pwd  #Multiple cmds



Commands-Directories

mkdir /tmp/asia                   #Make Directory Hirechary       ----------------->            mkdir -p /tmp/asia/india/bangalore
mkdir /tmp/asia/india
mkdir /tmp/asia/india/bangalore

rm -r /tmp/my_dir1                #Remove Directory

cp -r my_dir1 /tmp/my_dir1        #Copy Directory


Commands-Files

touch new_file.txt                #Create a new file (no contents)

cat > new-file.txt                #Add contents to file
This is somple sample contents
Ctrl + D

cat new_file.txt                  #View contents of file
cp new_file.txt sample_file.txt   #Copy File
mv new_file.txt sample_file.txt   #Move(Rename) File
rm new_file.txt                   #Remove(Delete) File

Three types of Editors on Linux:

1. Vi #Commonly used
2. Vim
3. nano

Shortcut keys

x ---> #to delete a char
dd --> #to delete entire line
yy and p --> #to paste entire line
:wq! ---> #save and quit
/xyz ----> #find any word inside the editor file


USER ACCOUNTS

whoami    #to know the user
id        #number of uid
su xyz       #switch user
ssh xyz@a.b.c.d #switch from to desired user using ip
sudo ls /root   #on root user has all previlages
/etc/sudoers

DOWNLOAD FILES

curl -O http://www.google.com
        OR
wget http://www.google.com -O teja.txt  #COMMONLY USED


CHECK OS VERSION

ls /etc*release*  #list OS data
cat /etc*release* #Give detail info about OS


